(Recently, Verisimilitude left a comment on this entry of mine about binding TCP and UDP ports) Tj
T*
(to a specific address. That got me thinking about features that have become standard elements) Tj
T*
(of things despite not being officially specified and required. TCP and UDP are more or less) Tj
T*
(officially specified in various RFCs and are implicitly specified by what happens on the wire.) Tj
T*
(As far as I know, nowhere in these standards \(or wire behavior\) does anything require that a) Tj
T*
(multi-address host machine allow you to listen for incoming TCP or UDP traffic on a specific) Tj
T*
(port on only a restricted subset of those addresses. People talking to your host have to use a) Tj
T*
(specific IP, obviously, and established TCP connections have specific IP addresses associated) Tj
T*
(with them that can't be changed, but that's it. Hosts could have an API where you simply) Tj
T*
(listened to a specific TCP or UDP port and then they provided you with the local IP when you) Tj
T*
(received inbound traffic; it would be up to your program to do any filtering to reject) Tj
T*
(addresses that you didn't want used. However, I don't think anyone has such an API, and) Tj
T*
(anything that did would likely be considered very odd and 'non-standard'. It's become an imp...) Tj
T*
() Tj
